body:

- [x] Run `npm run lint package-name` (or `tsc` if no `tslint.json` is present).

A breaking change was introduced in recent typescript 3.1 nightly builds, likely due to [changes in how arrays interact with mapping types](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/pull/26063). Unfortunately, `@types/ember` relied on the old behavior (removed by https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/pull/26063) in order to infer the type of a computed property.

https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/b77ae9d43b3df2caf0e23757d6b8bc96c3e8f1b9/types/ember/index.d.ts#L33-L34
(in the above example, imagine that `T` is an array, and you'll understand why our types for [`array.firstObject`](https://emberjs.com/api/ember/3.1/classes/MutableArray/properties/firstObject?anchor=firstObject) broke)

@dwickern [suggested](https://github.com/typed-ember/ember-cli-typescript/issues/246#issuecomment-414776161) (and I agree) that we shift toward using `infer` for extracting the wrapped type, which unfortunately means dropping support for all TypeScript versions below 2.8 (this is consistent with our policy of [supporting _at least_ the latest two TS releases](https://github.com/typed-ember/ember-cli-typescript/issues/246#issuecomment-414147777) )

I'm deliberately not adding additional tests, to ensure that this fix takes care of the tests broken in master, and keeps the rest passing with no additional changes required.

Related: https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/issues/26120
Fixes https://github.com/typed-ember/ember-cli-typescript/issues/246 
Fixes https://github.com/typed-ember/ember-cli-typescript/issues/226

body:

- [x] Run `npm run lint package-name` (or `tsc` if no `tslint.json` is present).

## Backstory for this change

Concider the following code:
```typescript
interface GUserAttributes {
    id? : number;
    username? : string;
    email: string;
}

interface GUserInstance extends Sequelize.Instance<GUserAttributes> {}
const GUser = s.define<GUserInstance, GUserAttributes>('user', {
    id: Sequelize.INTEGER,
    username: Sequelize.STRING
});
```

Before this PR there wasn't any error although `email` field is required and it is not defined inside `define`

But with this PR exactly the same code gives you an error
```
[ts]
Argument of type '{ id: DataTypeInteger; username: DataTypeString; }' is not assignable to parameter of type 'DefineModelAttributes<GUserAttributes>'.
  Property 'email' is missing in type '{ id: DataTypeInteger; username: DataTypeString; }'.
```

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12229968/44466969-533acd80-a62a-11e8-8e8c-6cba35b1d71d.png)

So you as a developer are more safe and can fix the error like so:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12229968/44467048-9301b500-a62a-11e8-8477-c6bd24c5959b.png)


What do you guys think? :)

title: [chrome] Change chrome-cast's class-like interfaces to class definitions.
body:
**TL;DR**: This avoids TS2339 when calling the constructor of these classes, e.g.
`new chrome.cast.SessionRequest(...)`.

**Issue Description:**

I ran into an issue when trying to use the existing chrome-cast type definitions. I wanted to create new instances of `chrome.cast.SessionRequest` and `chrome.cast.ApiConfig`, but the compiler returned with the following errors:

```
TS2339: Property 'SessionRequest' does not exist on type 'typeof cast'.
TS2339: Property 'ApiConfig' does not exist on type 'typeof cast'.
```

I figured out that this is because theses classes are currently defined as class-like interfaces and thus can not be instantiated. My changes are fixing this issue for me.
